##### HTTP 1.1 #####

A web server must implement the following features in order to fully comply with the HTTP/1.1 specification:

1. Persistent Connections: HTTP/1.1 supports persistent connections, allowing multiple requests to be sent over a single connection. 
   The server must implement this feature to fully support HTTP/1.1.

2. Improved Header Fields: HTTP/1.1 provides more header fields, allowing more information to be sent with each request. 
   The server must implement these additional header fields to be fully HTTP/1.1 compliant.

3. Host Header Field: HTTP/1.1 requires the use of the "Host" header field in all requests, 
   which indicates the domain name of the server being requested. The server must implement this header field to be fully HTTP/1.1 compliant.

4. Chunked Transfers: HTTP/1.1 supports chunked transfers, which allow data to be sent in chunks, rather than all at once. 
   The server must implement this feature to fully support HTTP/1.1.

5. Content Negotiation: HTTP/1.1 introduces content negotiation, 
   which allows the server to return different versions of a resource based on the client's preferences. 
   The server must implement this feature to fully support HTTP/1.1.

6. Conditional Requests: HTTP/1.1 also introduces conditional requests, 
   which allow clients to request only the parts of a resource that have changed since a previous request. 
   The server must implement this feature to fully support HTTP/1.1.

7. Cache Control: HTTP/1.1 introduces cache control mechanisms, 
   which allow the server to specify how a resource should be cached by the client or intermediate proxies. 
   The server must implement these mechanisms to be fully HTTP/1.1 compliant.